statement.tex:
\text{Find the values of a and b so that}\\
\text{the function defined by} \\
f(x)=\begin{cases}
  5, x\leq 2 \\
  ax + b, 2\lt x\lt 10 \\
  21, x\geq 10
\end{cases}
\\ \text{is a continuous function.}

step.tex:
f(x)\text{ can be discontinuous at }x=2\text{ and }x=10.\\
\text{Hence, for }f(x)\text{ to be continuous, it must be}\\
\begin{align}
  &\bullet\,\text{Continuous at x=2}\\
  &\bullet\,\text{Continuous at x = 10}
\end{align}

f(x)\text{ can be discontinuous only at }x=10. \\
\text{Hence, for }f(x)\text{ to be continuous, it must be}\\
\begin{align}
  &\bullet\,\text{Continuous at x = 10}
\end{align}

step.reason:
\text{Any point where the definition of a function}\\
\text{changes, like x = 2 and x = 10, could be a}\\
\text{potential point for discontinuity. Look there first.}

step.tex:
\text{At x = 2}\\
\begin{align}
  \lim_{x\to 2^-}f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 2^-} 5 = 5 \\
  \lim_{x\to 2^+}f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 2^+} (ax+b) = 2a+b \\
  f(2) &= 5
\end{align}
\\ \text{And at x = 10}\\
\begin{align}
  \lim_{x\to 10^-}f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 10^-} (ax+b) = 10a + b \\
  \lim_{x\to 10^+}f(x) &= \lim_{x\to 10^+} 21 = 21 \\
  f(10) &= 21
\end{align}
\\ \text{Which means, for f(x) to be continuous}\\
\begin{align}
  2a + b &= 5 \\
  10 + b &= 21 \implies a = 2, b = 1
\end{align}

step.reason:
\text{We have simply applied the condition for} \\
\text{continuity at x = 2 and x = 10. This gave us two}\\
\text{equations - which we solved to get a and b.}
